04460nam a22004575i 9781447342458DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20062006xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781447342458  a(DE-B1597)646457  a(OCoLC)1371574248  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0250002bisacsh1 aGibson, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBASW/Policy Press titles. Order from chaos :bResponding to traumatic events /cMarion Gibson. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBASW/Policy Press titles00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables and figures -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on the author -- tOrder from chaos -- tDisasters -- tPsychosocial reactions in traumatic incidents -- tResponding to psychosocial reactions -- tThe injured and their relatives -- tThe bereaved -- tCrisis situations associated with children -- tResponders and the process of responding -- tTheoretical approaches to responding -- tThe response of systems to traumatic events -- tResponders: research into the impact of their work -- tModular training programme for responders -- tThe challenge of bringing order from chaos -- tBibliography -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the context of recent natural disasters and the increase of global terrorism, there is a need for a greater understanding of the psychosocial impact of such events on the individuals and communities involved. This understanding can also enhance the support offered to people sho have to face trauma in their individual lives. Those who provide such a response need to develop their skills in this area of work. They too need to feel that they are supported in their work. This revised and expanded edition of a highly successful book consolidates the core elements of good proctice while bringing theory and practice issues up to date. As with the first and second editions, this book can be used as a guide for best practice and as a resource for instant reference when staff are faced with responding to traumatic incidents. It also provides up-to-date case studies, drawing on the author's knowledge and experience and points the way for further, more specialised study. The book identifies core elements that are common to most traumatic events; discusses practical methods of intervention that are based on analysis of contemporary research and best practice in a multidisciplinary context; shows how the skills discussed can be transferred to individual clinical practice; addresses the needs of responders and the responsibility of organisations to provide a 'duty of care' for those who are exposed to trauma in their occupational roles and presents a modular programme of training, devised by the author, to prepare responders in the pre-crisis period. Order from chaos is essential reading for all those who are or may be involved in supporting those who are experiencing the impact of trauma in their lives. It is also an invaluable resource for trainers in the field, and for social work and health and social care students and their teachers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aParkes, Colin Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z978311119621340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447342458423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447342458/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  